troubled youth.

43:15.827 --> 43:19.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEMUEL LAROCHE, University of
Georgia School
of Social Work: These kids are
looking for

43:19.630 --> 43:21.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
opportunities, looking for a way
out, bouncing
from foster home to foster
homes.

43:21.466 --> 43:25.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: And, to
that end,
LaRoche puts all of his teaching
skills to

43:25.203 --> 43:30.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
work with troubled and
not-so-troubled youth,
and others from other places,
with chess,

43:30.875 --> 43:33.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the game he loves and sees as
more than a
game.

43:33.845 --> 43:38.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEMUEL LAROCHE: While in Israel,
I got an
opportunity to play chess with
this old Russian

43:38.616 --> 43:40.451 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
man.

43:40.485 --> 43:45.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
